Rating: 4
Heavenly! I was thrilled to see the looks of the Thanksgiving guests when they took their first spoonful. Like another reviewer, I sliced the mushrooms closer to 1/8 inch. I used a wok to cook both the mushrooms and the leeks, then transferred them to a soup pot for simmering in the broth. It really is important to brown the mushrooms. I let them cook until all of the released liquid had evaporated and all the sizzling had stopped. I used half the amount of butter, which worked out just fine. I did not do the flour thing. Just didn't seem right with the delicate flavors. Instead, when the soup was finished, I pureed about a cup and added it back to the pot. The texture was perfect that way. And, as others have said, don't omit the thyme cream. That plus a tiny garnish of thyme tips made a gorgeous presentation, and the cream added just the right amount of richness.

Rating: 4
The critical thing to remember when cooking classic French style dishes such as this is that the flavours are not supposed to be complex. They feature a small number of fresh, simple ingredients cooked with traditional skills, and the goal is to turn them into a dish with lovely gentle nuances of flavour. But I must emphasize that technique is everything. We live in a delightfully multicultural world, and the skills required for one cuisine often don't apply to another. (Honestly, I'm happy they don't - the world would be so boring!) When I was in French Culinary school we used to compete: With ingredients from the same 'frig and the exact same recipes we vied for best flavour. It was always the same winners - the ones who were really solid on French technique. So if this recipe isn't working well for you, cut it and yourself some slack. French cooking is deceptively challenging, because with only a few ingredients the classic techniques are all you really have.

