Rating: 3
Have to agree with previous negative reviews. Not bad, just not that special. In this case, the thyme cream business is just presentation silliness that is putting the cart in front of the horse. Not sure if I agree w/ previous descriptions of the soup being "bland" since I associate that w/ undersalting. However, I will say that the flavor of the soup is quite simple and I don't think "leeks, mushrooms, and thyme soup" qualifies as anything special. And, yes, wife and mother both said it was awesome - don't let that fool you. So, I made this last night cream and all and we ate about half of it. Today I was unhappy with the state of my cast iron skillet and once I was done re-seasoning it I was going to fry something no matter what. Starting with one unlucky white onion I made the following changes to the s oup (1/2 recipe!) - 1 baseball-sized white onion chopped 1/4" dice - 1 Tbsp unsalted butter. - fry onion in butter slowly taking perhaps 30 minutes to achieve nice light brown color. - add 1 roughly chopped chipotle pepper (IMPORTANT!) - add 1 clove minced garlic. Fry some more even more slowly - add another TSP fresh chopped thyme - add 1 TBSP fresh chopped cilantro. To finish I added a tsp or two of low-sodium Knorr's chicken bouillon and fried it for about 2 more minutes. I removed heat and added two cups of water. Then I put the entire mixture into the blender and blended it until smooth. Finally, I poured the finished product back into the leftover soup from last night. Much improved.

